example.p:
Therefore, the total mass of the bar is measured by the corresponding Riemann sum 
(and the integral that it approximates)

  \sum_{i=1}^n \rho(x_i) \Delta x \approx \int_0^b \rho(x) \, dx=\text{mass}_{\text{total}}
. 
(As usual, the Riemann sum is an approximation,
while the integral will be the exact mass.)

solution.p:
For us, the maximum radius is R=5 miles, so the total amount of oil is


  \displaystyle \int_{0}^5 (150e^{-r^2})(2\pi r)\,  dr = \left.-150 \pi e^{-r^2} \right|_0^5 \\
  (-150\pi e^{-(5)^2}) - (-150\pi e^{-(0)^2})=471.23 \text{ barrels}

For us, the maximum radius is R=6 miles, so the total population is


  \displaystyle \int_{0}^6 ((1000-100r)(2\pi r)\,  dr = \left. 1000 \pi r^2-\frac{200\pi}{3}r^3 \right|_0^6 \\
  (1000 \pi (6)^2 - \frac{200 \pi}{3} (6)^3) - (0) \approx 67858 \text{ people}

li.p:
We must take the integral:
\text{mass}= \int_0^R 4 \pi r^2 \rho(r)\, dr = \int_0^{6300} 4 \pi r^2(-0.0016r+13)\, dr \\ = \left. 4\pi(-0.0004 r^4+\frac{13}{3}r^3) \right |_0^{6300}\\ \approx 5.7 \times 10^{12}
so the mass of the earth is roughly 5.7 \times 10^{12} trillions of kilograms.

If we have an existing arrangement and balancing point,
moving one of the locations to the left will move the balancing point to the left;
similarly,
moving one of the locations to the right will move the balancing point to the right.
If instead we add weight to an existing location,
if that location is left of the balancing point,
the balancing point will move left;
the behavior is similar if on the right.

If we have an existing arrangement and balancing point,
moving one of the locations to the left will move the balancing point to the left;
similarly,
moving one of the locations to the right will move the balancing point to the right.
If instead we add weight to an existing location,
